# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: criticism-of-coca-cola
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The **2017 pro-jallikattu protests**, also known as the **pro-jallikattu movement**, were leaderless apolitical youth protests which took place in January 2017 in large groups in several locations across the Indian state of Tamil Nadu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Some sporadic smaller protests also took place across India as well as overseas.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The chief motivation of the protest was against the Supreme Court's order to ban jallikattu (occasionally also known as *sallikattu*, *eru taluval and* *manju virattu*), a traditional Tamil bull taming sport, which is held during Pongal, a harvest festival in the state of Tamil Nadu, India.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The sport is conducted annually on the second day of the Tamil month Thai.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The sport was banned by the Supreme Court in a decision citing cruelty to animals based on a lawsuit filed by the animal rights group People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA), which asserted that it violates the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act (PCA).
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The first large protests occurred on 8 January 2017, when several groups, organised largely via social media, conducted a protest at the Marina beach in Chennai to revoke the ban on jallikattu which was imposed in 2014.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] These groups also demanded that PETA be banned from India.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protests soon gained momentum and spread all over Tamil Nadu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] After several days of protests, jallikattu was finally legalised locally on 23 January when the Government of Tamil Nadu passed a bill to amend the PCA Act.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] As the legalisation is not Indian federal law, but rather state law, there is concern from Indian legal experts that jallikattu could be banned once again by the Supreme Court.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The largely peaceful nature of the protests received praise from all over the country and inspired the legalisation movements of several other Indian states' traditional outlawed celebrations.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Despite violence on 23 January, this perception continued after the Tamil Nadu Police reported that the violence was caused by "anti-social elements" co-opting the protest, and not the student protesters themselves.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The movement has been described as a symbol for Tamil pride and has largely been compared to the anti-Hindi agitations of Tamil Nadu and dubbed by many as 'Thai Puratchi'.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The sport, which is considered to be 2500–10,000 years old, is usually held during Thai Pongal across several locations in Tamil Nadu, with the primary event being held in Alanganallur.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] During the event, injuries or even death often occur to participants.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] While bull breeders contend that the participating bulls are treated well, PETA asserts its investigators found that the bulls suffers cruel treatment, from having their tails twisted, being stabbed, punched and jumped on.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] India's Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act (PCAA) outlaws animal cruelty, and sets up the punishment offenders can expect to receive.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The Madras High Court was the first to rule that jallikattu was not allowable under the PCAA in 2006.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] However, traditional sports like jallikattu have since then always been allowed through various legal and extralegal means, the most recent of which is the Tamil Nadu Regulation of Jallikattu Act No 27, passed by the Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly and signed into law in 2009.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Armed with this, in April 2011, PETA announced that it would challenge the 2009 Tamil Nadu law as unconstitutional, as it now conflicts with the Indian federal law.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] After three years in court, on 7 May 2014, PETA, represented by Raj Panjwani, along with the Animal Welfare Board of India (AWBI), striking down the 2009 Tamil Nadu law.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] In defiance of the ban, citizens of Tamil Nadu attempted to carry out the tradition on 18 January 2015, but police arrested forty six people and allowed the animals to go free.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] In preparation for the 2016 jallikattu season, the Centre reversed its earlier decision and on 7 January 2016 MoE once again removed bulls from the list of banned performing animals.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] With the police on their side this time, however, jallikattu went ahead anyway, and thousands gathered to watch bull races and the main sport.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] In preparation for the 2017 season, once again multiple petitions were filed to try to get the Supreme Court to reconsider; and once again they were all denied, including a petition attempting to argue a religious freedom angle.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The Supreme Court once again sparred with the Centre, who was trying to get it unbanned as it was a 5,000-year-old cultural tradition of the Tamil people, but the court responded simply "In 1899, ten thousand girls below 12 years of age were married.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Should we allow it today because it was a tradition at that time?" and rejected the petition.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] For the 2017 season, political tension was high, perhaps sparking the massive protest: people blamed the AIADMK and BJP political parties for failing to reverse the ban during the last three years.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Once again, citizens flouted the Supreme Court, and jallikattu went ahead despite its legal status.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] In an interview, former Supreme Court justice Markandey Katju observed that laws can be changed even when the matter is in court as was done for the act that abolished *zamindari* in the 1950s when the Nehru government removed the right to property as a fundamental right.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Native breed activists claim that Tamil Nadu had over one million Kangayam bulls in 1990 and that the population has fallen to 15,000 by the 2010s.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Minor protests were initiated by cattle rights activists and farmers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Music videos, such as "Takkaru Takkaru" by Hiphop Tamizha, and on Facebook videos to talk about jallikattu and its benefits inspired the protestors.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] There were also claims that the indigenous cattle bulls are critically endangered in Tamil Nadu and banning jallikattu will have the adverse effect of wiping them out completely.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] According to pro-jallikattu activists, jallikattu is not just a sport that is deeply entrenched in Tamil culture, but it has also inadvertently served as a scientific method of breeding cattle.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] This view is held among a majority of jallikattu supporters.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protest is aimed at revival of the native humped bull, called the zebu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The Tamil Nadu breed of zebu is unique to India and has several advantages compared to European varieties of cattle such as the Holstein cow.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The native breeds are rich in the A2 variety of beta casein protein which aides easy digestion whereas milk from European *Bos taurus* contain the A1 variant of the beta casein protein which is related to allergies and some serious health conditions.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The Holstein breeds found their way into India as a result of Operation Flood of late 1960s through cross breeding to increase the low milk yield of native breeds.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] As the Jersey cow can yield nine times the quantity of milk as a zebu in the same period, there is concern among protesters that without jallikattu providing an economic incentive for the breeding of zebu, the breed will become endangered and eventually extinct.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] PETA disputes the allegation that outlawing jallikattu would lead to a loss of the Tamil Nadu zebu, stating that the bulls can still be used as studs regardless of whether jallikattu is legal or not.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Support from various groups, including film actors, politicians, cricketers and other sportsmen, social activists, and authors.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Raghava Lawrence, actor Silambarasan, director V.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Gowthaman, Seeman, Samuthirakani, Ameer, RJ Balaji, Aari, Mansoor Ali Khan and G.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Prakash Kumar took part actively during the protests.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Spiritual leaders like Sri Sri Ravi Shankar, and Sadhuguru Jaggi Vasudev also spoke in support of the sport.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protestors rejected any attempt for leadership by politicians and celebrities and wished to remain a leaderless mass movement.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Rahman announced that he will observe a day-long fast in support of the protesters, and for 'Tamil Nadu's spirit'.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The main opposition of jallikattu comes from the Indian branch of the international non-governmental organization People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA).
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] PETA's opposition is also shared by the Animal Welfare Board of India (AWBI), Federation of Indian Animal Protection Organisations and Compassion Unlimited Plus Action (CUPA).
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Judges of the Supreme Court of India have likewise criticized the Indian Central Government's support of jallikattu just because it is a tradition and have voiced their opposition of it.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The Supreme Court has also held that the sport is inherently cruel in nature and this deprives the animal of its basic right to live without subject to fear and torture.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The judgement also clarifies that the sport is neither religious ritual nor an essential sport for the Tamil community as the sport is played only in few districts of central Tamil Nadu and not in all districts.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The sport has claimed multiple lives including those of the tamers, onlookers and the police.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The first ban on jallikattu was a result of a case filed by the father of a tamer who lost his life in the event.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] PETA denies that ending the jallikattu event will lead to the loss of the native bull, and has pointed out that bulls can be used as studs regardless of whether or not they are engaged in jallikattu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Furthermore, PETA claims that veterinarians can determine which bulls are healthiest with far more scientific rigor than jallikattu can.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Sporadic demonstrations began on 4 January, but mass protests did not begin until two weeks later.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 16 January 2017, villagers of Alanganallur protested at Alanganallur '*Vaadi vaasal*' – The Arena, the place known for the jallikattu sport – on that date, the sport was also practiced in defiance of the ban.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] After a day long protest, police arrested the protesters numbering around 200 in Madurai.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 17 January 2017, In support of the arrested, Students gathered in Marina Beach.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] This day incidentally coincided with the birth centenary of former Tamil Nadu Chief Minister M.G.Ramachadran.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The crowds started swelling for the night and few hundred spent their night in beach and the crowds continued to gather strength throughout the next day.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protest erupted around the state including Salem, Erode, Coimbatore, Nagercoil, Thiruchrapalli, Pudhuchery.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 19 January, many volunteer groups and individuals once again gathered at the Marina beach for overnight protests. deputy Tamil Nadu Chief Minister O.Paneerselvam met Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi and pushed for an ordinance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] With no sign of protests relenting the centre suggested ordinance by Tamil Nadu Government.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 20 January, The draft ordinance was approved by Home, Environmental and Cultural Ministry.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On this day the Marina beach Witnessed around 20 lakh protesters on peaceful Occupy Marina protest alone with lacs thronging various cities of state..
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The day witnessed a virtual shutdown in the state as most organization downed their shutters expressing solidarity for the cause.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The Opposition party Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK) staged Rail Roko in district headquarters of the state.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 21 January, the protests still continue demanding a permanent solution.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Some politicians of the opposition parties started fasting as a sign of protest.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The State Government promulgated the ordinance and announced that it would conduct the event the next day.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] However the protesters refused to budge, as they believe the ordinance has very weak legal grounds and could be overturned in much the same way as the Supreme Court overturned the 2009 ordinance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 22 January, the government tried to conduct the sport despite the opposition from the local people in Alanganallur and other parts of Tamil Nadu who demanded a permanent resolution which can ensure jallikattu for generations to come.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protesters had successfully blocked the sport from being conducted as Government festival.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] However a jallikattu event was organised and held at Pudukottai without proper safety measures on a very short notice and was inaugurated by the government minister, which eventually killed two people and many were left injured.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 23 January, with protesters refusing to budge, police began early morning forceful evictions, moving people by hand and also employing batons.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Protesters at the marina threatened to venture into the sea, but eventually most protesters were removed and access to the protest site was cut off.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The evictions led to further protesters and threaten to boycott the upcoming Republic Day celebrations in Chennai beach.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The entire city came to standstill with protesters blocking major roads and incidents of stone pelting torching of vehicles, police stations and petrol bombs were thrown whose identity remain unknown.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] There have also been reports of police involving in burning of autos and vehicles.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The videos of cop setting fire on vehicles and involving in arson have been going viral in social media.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The initial organizers of protests called for calm and few including actors condemned the violence and the subsequent crackdown.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] At the end of day most of protests were either withdrawn evacuated or forcefully at all places including at Marina Beach, Madurai, Salem, Erode and Coimbatore and normalcy started to be restored.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The legal situation surrounding jallikattu is as yet not clearly resolved.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] While the Tamil Nadu government has claimed that its draft ordinance is a "permanent solution", many jallikattu supporters view it as merely being a "stop gap measure".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] As ordinances only last for six months, the Tamil Nadu Assembly plans to make the ordinance into state law "immediately".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Some, however such as Ministry of External Affairs cabinet minister Salman Khurshid, have stated that the matter will only be truly resolved if the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act is amended as local ordinances and state laws cannot trump Indian federal law.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] According to *The Hindu*, many other Indian legal experts agreed with Khurshid's view, as federal laws such as the PCA are always more powerful than state laws, and in that respect the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (Tamil Nadu Amendment) Act of 2017 is not much different from the 2009 one.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 24 January, in light of the new Tamil Nadu legislation, the Centre withdrew its notification allowing the sport; this means that any new legal challenges will be directed against the new legislation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] For its part, PETA India has said that it will "study" the new ordinance, and has not ruled out a challenge to the new law on the same grounds as it challenged the 2009 law.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 25 January, the Animal Welfare Board of India (AWBI) restarted the legal process by formally challenging the new law before the Supreme Court, but it withdrew the petition the next day.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] According to the AWBI's acting chairperson, AWBI does not plan to re-file the petition, but he claimed no knowledge of what other organizations, such as PETA, may do.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 6 July 2017, PETA India released a YouTube video showing the results of their investigation of five Jallikattu events which took place across Tamil Nadu in February 2017.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] According to PETA, their investigation showed abuse of the animals during the February events, including the tails of bulls being bitten and twisted, collapsed bulls being pulled by ropes attached to their noses, and bulls having their tailbones purposefully broken.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] In an interview with *The Hindu*, organisers of the events denied the claims of PETA.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 7 July 2017, PETA filed a petition with the Supreme Court of India seeking a renewed ban on Jallikattu via the invalidation of the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (Tamil Nadu Amendment) Act of 2017 as unconstitutional.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] On 2 February 2018, the Supreme Court of India accepted PETA's petition, referring the case to its constitution bench.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protests were spontaneous and had no specific organizers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protest started as Occupy Marina protest along with sit-ins at large grounds across the state.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protests were initially formed by members of Student community across the state which was further strengthened by people from various sections such as IT professionals who joined later.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The lack of leader was seen as stumbling block for the state government because it could not call people for talks.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protest were largely peaceful except few Baton charge by the police.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Tamil youths from other states express solidarity with jallikattu protesters in Tamil Nadu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] There was demonstration in Bengaluru, Mumbai, Ahmedabad, and Delhi.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Support for the protest also came from Tamils around the world such as in Sri Lanka, the United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, New Zealand, Singapore, Malaysia, Canada, China, Russia, Switzerland, Ireland, Japan, the United Arab Emirates, the United States, France, South Africa, and Finland.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The protest was primarily coordinated using social media apps.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] The use of memes has been another feature to spread the message that adds satire and humor to the protests.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Various traditional Tamil sports such as Silambattam, stilt performances and street plays are performed to showcase Tamil pride along with speeches to inspire the crowd.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Slogans were shouted against the animal rights organization PETA, alleging an international conspiracy favoring extinction of Tamil Nadu's rare cattle breed, and replacing them with Jersey cows from Denmark and Switzerland.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Traders and various colleges in Tamil Nadu have called for the ban on aerated multi-national brands like Pepsi and Coca-Cola with effect from 1 March 2017 and replace them with localised drinks like tender coconut and fresh juices.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Poor public turn out on the Republic day parade in Chennai, condemning the Police charge on the students.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2017-pro-jallikattu-protests] Declaration of Marina as out of bounds for future protests.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The rights to the A&W brand (except in Canada) are owned by Keurig Dr Pepper, which in turn licenses the brand to the U.S.-based A&W Restaurant chain.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] A&W Root Beer products are distributed via various U.S. bottlers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] A&W Food Services of Canada, which is independent of both Keurig Dr Pepper and the U.S. restaurant chain, is responsible for the restaurants and marketing of root beer products in Canada, with retail products bottled and distributed by the Coca-Cola Company.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The U.S. variant is also sold as an import drink in Southeast Asia and Italy (where A&W has restaurants), as well as in Australia, Chile, and other countries.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Allen opened a roadside root beer stand in Lodi, California in 1919, using a formula he had purchased from a pharmacist.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] He soon opened stands in Stockton, and five stands in nearby Sacramento where "tray boys" pioneered drive-in curbside service.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1922, Allen partnered with Frank Wright, birthing the A&W brand name.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Allen bought Wright out, obtained a trademark, and began selling restaurant franchises - creating one of the early restaurant chains in the United States.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Franchise owners could use the A&W name and logo and purchased concentrated root beer syrup from Allen.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] However, there was no common menu, architecture, or set of procedures, and some chose to sell food as well.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] During World War II, franchisees struggled with labor shortages and sugar rationing, but after the war the number of A&W outlets tripled, helped in part by the availability of GI loans.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The proliferation of the automobile and the mobility it offered also led to growth; by 1950 there were more than 450 A&W Root Beer stands in operation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] That year, Allen retired and sold the business to Nebraskan Gene Hurtz, who formed the A&W Root Beer Company.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The first A&W Root Beer outlet in Canada opened in 1956.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] By 1960, the number of A&W restaurants swelled to more than 2,000.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Hungerford Smith Company, which had produced Allen's concentrate since 1921.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Also in 1963, the first overseas A&W restaurant opened in Guam.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1966, Hungerford was sold to the United Fruit Company, which merged with AMK Corporation in 1970 to form the United Brands Company.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1971, United Brands formed a wholly owned subsidiary, A&W Distributing Co., to retail its root beer.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] After test runs in Arizona and California (Phoenix, Tucson and San Diego), the products were distributed nationally, including sugar-free, low-sodium, and caffeine-free versions.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1974, A&W introduced "The Great Root Bear", a mascot that served as a goodwill ambassador for the brand.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The bear and its associated jingle became the basis of a long-running Canadian advertising campaign.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The mascot was so successful that it was eventually adopted by the American A&W chain as well.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] A&W Restaurants was formed in the late '70s to manage restaurant franchising.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1983, United Brands sold A&W Root Beer to a group of investors led by Castle & Cooke.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1984, it had an advertising budget of $10 million.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1986, Hicks & Haas and management bought A&W from the investor group.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] A&W Cream Soda and A&W Diet Cream Soda were introduced and distributed nationally in 1986, followed in 1987 by the reformulation of A&W Sugar-Free as Diet A&W.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The company went public in 1987 and also acquired Vernors.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In October 1993, A&W Beverages was folded into Cadbury Beverages.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] It spun off its U.S. beverages business as Dr Pepper Snapple Group in 2008.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In July 2017, A&W Canada reformulated its root beer, dropping high fructose corn syrup and some flavors from the recipe, substituting cane sugar, sarsaparilla root, licorice, birch bark and anise.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] A&W Canada launched the new formula by declaring Free Root Beer Day, serving free root beer at all locations on July 22, 2017.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In November 2020, Diet A&W was rebranded as A&W Zero Sugar.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The beverage made an advertising campaign in 1978 under the tagline "Now New York Has Everything", which was created to promote the arrival of A&W Root Beer in the New York metro area.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] For this end, the A&W Distributing Company signed a one-year $1 million advertising contract with Humphrey Browning MacDougall in March 1978.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The goal was to remedy its geographic disparities (although it was the leading root beer brand, at the time, it had a penetration of 46% of the national population) and was meant to boost sales of root beer, which was the fourth most-sold type of soft drink.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In the markets where it was available, it was advertised under its "frosty mug taste" tagline.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] New York received a special campaign featuring four 30-second spots about people from various parts of the United States who moved to New York and noticed the lack of the beverage.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] There was also a longer 60-second spot that ran on April 18, 1978 on the six commercial VHF stations in the area.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In July 1982, advertiser Scott Miller of Humphrey Browning MacDougall started becoming responsible for the product's hard sell.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In April 1984, a new commercial began circulating on American television.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] It emulated beer commercials on the onset, featuring two lumberjacks in a rustic tavern.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Halfway through the commercial, one of the lumberjacks was desiring a mug of A&W Root Beer.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] This campaign coincided with a change in its distribution scheme, which was now targeting truck drivers and sales representatives, who distributed the product to roughly half of the national population.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] For two periods during the summer of 1984, A&W would only advertise the floats.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The campaign was advertised on network TV, 90 media markets and, for the first time, cable, booking slots on MTV and WTBS, the latter during *Night Tracks*.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The sugar free version was set to be advertised alongside an exercise program on Lifetime.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] New commercials for the range of sodas began circulating in January 1991.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The three commercials featured former A-list celebrities, each one advertising a different product.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The cream soda commercial featured Dick Wilson (appearing in character as Mr.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Whipple from the Charmin commercials) squeezing a can of it, while the zero sugar version featured Jan Miner (as Madge from Palmolive).
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Both of the commercials did not feature their signature lines from their respective commercials.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] T, using his early 80s accessories, which the Chicago Tribune called "a symbol of a dead decade as Donald Trump".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In the summer of 1992, a campaign featuring David Leisure as Joe Isuzu was carried on American television, continuing A&W's fad of recovering older celebrities who starred in commercials.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The soda started using the "frosty mug taste" tagline in the fall of 1992, coinciding with its new packaging and plans to rebound its marketing for 1993.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In May 1999, it unveiled the "It's Good to be Thick Headed" campaign for network and cable.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] This consisted of three commercials: "Mr.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Dumass" (in which a job applicant mispronounces the name of the owner as "Mr.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Dumbass"), "Bachelor Party" (where a dim-witted husband and his wife are put inside a doghouse) and "Witness Protection".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] These commercials, whose target audience was mainly male sports fans, were discarded at the end of 2001 and set to be replaced by a new set of commercials for a broader demographic, as research revealed that the drink was also popular with teen girls.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The **Great Root Bear**, also called Rooty, became the mascot for A&W Root Beer in 1973.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In a long-running television advertising campaign for the Canadian A&W chain, his theme was a tuba-driven jingle entitled "Ba-Dum, Ba-Dum".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] The jingle was released as a single by Attic Records in Canada.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] It was credited to "Major Ursus", a play on the constellation name Ursa Major, which means "great bear".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Hall of Fame enshrinee Robert Buckley helped compose the song.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In late 2011, the new ownership of A&W began using the mascot again, particularly in A&W's online presence.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Shortly after Allen bought out Wright's portion of the business he began franchising the product.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] His profits came from a small franchise fee and sales of concentrate.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] There was no standard food menu for franchises until 1978.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] In 1989 A&W made an agreement with Minnesota-based chain Carousel Snack Bars to convert that chain's 200 locations (mostly kiosks in shopping malls) to "A&W Hot Dogs & More".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Some A&W Hot Dogs & More locations are in operation today.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Many A&W locations that opened in the U.S. during the Yum!
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Brands ownership years (2002–2011) were co-branded with Yum!'s other chains—Long John Silver's, Taco Bell, Pizza Hut or KFC.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] As of December 2011 A&W was under new ownership and its world headquarters was moved back to Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/a-w-root-beer] Since then, in the United States and Southeast Asia, A&W has been owned by a group of franchisees (as A Great American Brand).
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] Abbey Well was originally produced by Waters & Robson in the early 1980s.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] The name comes from a location near to the source of the water, a 12th century Cistercian Abbey, Newminster Abbey, one of the favourite places of the founder of the company, Thomas Robson.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] In 1981, a new bottling site was built in Morpeth, Northumberland to bottle Abbey Well at source.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] The company uses a 117-metre deep artesian well for its still water.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] As of 2008, the company had 91 employees, produced 30 million litres of water annually and had a turnover of £11 million.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] In 2000, the Abbey Well label featured a portrait of David Hockney by fellow artist, Peter Blake.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] At its source, Abbey Well filters through the area's white sandstone.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] In 2008, the manufacturer of Abbey Well, Waters & Robson, was acquired by Coca-Cola Enterprises.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] The acquisition of Abbey Well marked Coca-Cola's third foray into the UK water market after its previous attempts using the Dasani and Malvern brands.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] To meet Olympic branding regulations, Abbey Well water was labeled as "Still Water" for on-camera appearances during the Games.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] In 2014, £3.5 million was invested in the Morpeth site by Coca-Cola for the UK launch of Glaceau Smartwater.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] In 2016, £14 million was invested in the Morpeth site by Coca-Cola.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] Waters & Robson's Morpeth site is still used by Coca-Cola European Partners today for Abbey Well as well as for their Glaceau Smartwater product and Schweppes Soda Water.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/abbey-well] It is currently the only Coca-Cola water site in the UK.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/ades-brand] The soy-based beverage product was created in Argentina in 1988.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/ades-brand] The Coca-Cola Company entered into an agreement with Unilever on June 1, 2016, to acquire AdeS in Latin America.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/ades-brand] The bottled water product is currently made by PT Coca-Cola Bottling Indonesia in Bekasi, West Java, which also produces Coca-Cola, Fanta and Sprite.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] Chocolate and sugar skulls are used to decorate altars dedicated to the dead during the celebration.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] The fair starts in the middle of October and lasts up to the beginning of November.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] Hundreds of people sell their wares at Los Portales, a series of arches surrounding the so-called place, where people can go and buy their own skulls for their altars.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] Every year a contest takes places in order to give a prize to the best candy skull and to the best decorated business.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] This word was referred to the preparation of a pastry of cooked sugar stretched into very thin layers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] The alfeñique came along with the Spanish and then the aztecs made figurines with amaranth for their altars.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] These were known as the first alfeñiques in the New World.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] In colonial times, the nuns related the “alfeñique” as a traditional figurine for the months of October and November to celebrate *Día de Muertos*.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/alfeñique-fair] There is also an annual Alfeñique fair in the city of Guanajuato.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Since its invention by John Stith Pemberton in 1886, criticisms of Coca-Cola as a product, and of the business practices of The Coca-Cola Company, have been significant.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The Coca-Cola Company is the largest soft drink company in the world, distributing over 500 different products.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Since the early 2000s, the criticism of the use of Coca-Cola products, as well as the company itself, escalated, with criticism leveled at the company over health effects, environmental issues, animal testing, economic business practices and employee issues.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The Coca-Cola Company has been faced with multiple lawsuits concerning the various criticisms.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 1909, the Pure Food and Drug Act passed, and the United States government seized 40 barrels and 20 kegs of Coca-Cola syrup because they considered the added caffeine to be a harmful ingredient.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] One of the first noted criticisms of Coca-Cola was that it produced serious mental and motor deficits.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] This resulted in Coca-Cola's first lawsuit and trial where the official charges were that Coca-Cola was adulterated and misbranded.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The trial following the lawsuit, *The United States Government v.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Forty Barrels, Twenty Kegs Coca-Cola*, started in March 1911 a year and a half after the government had seized the barrels and kegs.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Harvey Washington Wiley, a chemist and head of the Bureau of Chemistry in the U.S.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Department of Agriculture led the lawsuit.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Wiley was anti Coca-Cola mainly because he was against the added caffeine.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The trial included many studies as well as paid testimonies from both parties and in the end was dismissed by the judge.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] However, the United States government ended up winning the case when they took it to the Supreme Court in 1916.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] This resulted in the reduction of caffeine content in Coca-Cola.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 1916, there was a federal suit under which the US government unsuccessfully attempted to force The Coca-Cola Company to remove caffeine from its products.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 1944, a waitress named Gladys Escola was putting away glass bottles of Coca-Cola when one of the bottles spontaneously exploded in her hand.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] She successfully sued the company, claiming they were liable.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Coca-Cola is rich in sugar, especially sucrose, which causes dental caries when consumed regularly.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Besides this, the high caloric value contributes to obesity.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Both are major health issues in the developed world.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Coca-Cola Co. partially funded the pro-industry advocacy group International Life Sciences Institute (ILSI) for many years prior to ending their support for the organization in 2021.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] ILSI was founded by a former Coca-Cola Co. executive in 1978, and has employed a number of former high level Coca-Cola Co. employees.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The organization promotes physical activity rather than dietary changes to address obesity, taking a position similar to Coca-Cola Co.-funded research and messaging.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In January 2009, the US consumer group the Center for Science in the Public Interest filed a class-action lawsuit against Coca-Cola.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The lawsuit was in regard to claims made, along with the company's flavors, of Vitamin Water.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Claims say that the 33 grams of sugar are more harmful than the vitamins and other additives are helpful.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In Catalonia, there has been controversy regarding Coca-Cola's refusal to print its labels in Catalan.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] On December 12, 1993, the Platform for the Catalan Language (Plataforma per la Llengua) managed to make a world record by bringing together more than 15,000 empty Coca-Cola cans in Barcelona's central square Plaça de Catalunya and using them to build a giant sign that read "Let's label in Catalan".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] At the time, the organisation adopted the motto: "The Coca-Cola label in 135 languages around the world, but not in Catalan?".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2014, POM Wonderful unsuccessfully argued that Coca-Cola's Minute Maid division had mislabeled a product as a pomegranate and blueberry juice, when it was made 99.4% from apple and grape juices.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] POM Wonderful said this labelling caused unfair loss of sales of its own pomegranate and blueberry juice.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In March 2004, local officials in Kerala shut down a $16 million Coke bottling plant blamed for a drastic decline in both quantity and quality of water available to local farmers and villagers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In April 2005, the Kerala High Court rejected water use claims, noting that wells there continued to dry up last summer, months after the local Coke plant stopped operating.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Further, a scientific study requested by the court found that while the plant had "aggravated the water scarcity situation," the "most significant factor" was a lack of rainfall.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The case has been appealed and a decision is pending.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2017, Coca-Cola declared that it had no plans to restart bottling operations in Plachimada, Kerala.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In June 2021, the factory was converted into a Covid-19 First Line treatment center.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In the investor summit held in Indore, Madhya Pradesh in 2016, the state government allocated land for Coca-Cola plant at Babai in Hoshangabad.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The government gave all the required permissions but did not publicize the Rs.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] 750 crore investment project due to the controversies of water exploitation by the company.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] It became a serious issue and Chief Minister Shivraj Singh Chouhan distanced himself from the project.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The residents of Babai opposed the project as the plant, when built, would consume tens of thousands of litres of water daily, thereby depleting the water level of the nearby river Narmada.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In order to stop the project, residents started a signature campaign to garner support for the cause and passed a resolution against the company.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] They also attacked state government that on one hand, it was talking about taking measures to save the river and on the other hand, gave permission to set up the plant.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The government canceled the land allocation in 2022, as Coca-Cola did not break ground on the plant within a five-year period, as was agreed-upon in the contract.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Coca-Cola stated that it decided against building the plant due to the company re-franchising.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In January 2017, Tamil Nadu Vanigar Sangangalin Peramaipu (TNVSP) called for its members to stop selling Coca-Cola and PepsiCo products to show solidarity with local farmers who had complained about groundwater depletion caused by these companies.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2016–17 Tamil Nadu experienced a severe drought which fueled the animosity.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] TNVSP consists of over 6,000 local trade associations covering about 1.5 million (15 Lakh) traders across Tamil Nadu, a southern Indian state.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The boycott came into effect from March 1, and the majority of the small and medium-sized vendors were reported to have stopped stocking the products.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The boycott gained momentum during the Jallikattu protests.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Packaging used in Coca-Cola's products has a significant environmental impact.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The company is the single largest plastic polluter in the world, producing over 3 million tonnes of plastic packaging each year.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The head of sustainability Bea Perez has said they will continue to use plastic, stating "customers like them because they reseal and are lightweight" and that they create a lower carbon footprint than aluminum and glass bottles.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The company has opposed attempts to introduce mechanisms such as container deposit legislation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2013, the company was criticized in Australia for undertaking litigation that led to the invalidation of a bottle recycling deposit.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2017 Greenpeace published a report criticizing Coca-Cola's use of single-use plastic bottles.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The report is especially critical of the company's failing to reach the goals it set to source 25% of its bottles from recycled or renewable sources, and the non-existence of targets to reduce its use of single-use bottles since then.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2022, Greenpeace stated that it welcomed Coca-Cola’s pledge to make 25% of its packaging reusable by 2030.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2015, the company was accused of 27 Clean Air Act violations at a Minute Maid plant in Michigan.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In May 2014, Coca-Cola reached a settlement with the EPA for these violations, in which it paid $165,900 in civil penalties.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2007, the Coca-Cola Company announced it would no longer conduct or directly fund laboratory experiments on animals unless required by law to do so.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The company's announcement came after PETA criticized the company for funding invasive experiments on animals including one study in which experimenters cut into the face of chimpanzees to study the animals' nerve impulses used in the perception of sweet taste.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Some experimenters have criticized PETA's campaign against Coca-Cola and other companies claiming that their work would be stalled if they lost corporate funding.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2000, a United States federal judge dismissed an antitrust lawsuit filed by PepsiCo Inc. accusing Coca-Cola Co. of monopolizing the market for fountain-dispensed soft drinks in the United States.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In June 2005, Coca-Cola in Europe formally agreed to end deals with shops and bars to stock its drinks exclusively after a European Union investigation found its business methods stifled competition.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In November 2005, Coca-Cola's Mexican unit – Coca-Cola Export Corporation – and a number of its distributors and bottlers were fined $68 million for unfair commercial practices.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] On July 7, 2008, Coca-Cola Co compromised to pay $137.5 million to settle an October 2000 shareholder lawsuit.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The settlement applies to Coca-Cola common stock owners from October 21, 1999, to March 6, 2000.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Coca-Cola entered South Africa in 1938 and, after the beginning of the official white South African government's policy of apartheid or "separate development" beginning in 1948, the company grew rapidly.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] By the 1980s at the height of racial oppression, with 90% of the market, Coke dominated the soft-drink industry with sales in the hundreds of millions of dollars, accounting for 5% of the parent company's global market.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Coke employed 4,500 workers, operating under the racially segregated system of housing, workplace, and wages, and was one of the largest employers in the country.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 1982 in South Africa, black workers asked the community to boycott Coke and called two work stoppages until the company agreed to recognize and bargain with their union, raise its workers' low wages significantly, and share information on who controls their pension fund.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] As a result of Coke's economic support of white South Africa and its apartheid system, in the 1980s, it became a major target of organizers across the country against U.S. and corporate economic support for apartheid in the U.S.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Boycotts then spread across the country to many universities including Tennessee State, Penn State, and Compton College in California, which established a "Coke Free Campus".
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Demonstrations were held by the Georgia Coalition and the AFSC at Coca-Cola's Atlanta headquarters.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] After democratic elections that produced Mandela's majority rule government, Pepsi sought to re-enter the South African market.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In fact, "Coke never truly left the country, leading to overwhelming dominance through the rest of the 20th century.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Pepsi adhered to different social imperatives and suffered exceptionally low market shares as a result." Indeed, in the late 2000s, Coke's market share of the soft drink market in South Africa was estimated at 95% and Pepsi's at 2%.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2001, Coca-Cola reportedly paid Warner Brothers, a unit of Time Warner $150 million for the exclusive global marketing rights to at least one Harry Potter movie and subsequently enticing children to drink more soft drinks, a move criticized by the Center for Science in the Public Interest.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Health experts stated that the non-profit's message was misleading and part of Coke to deflect criticism about the role the company played in the spread of obesity and Type 2 diabetes.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] On May 7, 2017, *Haaretz* published that Coca-Cola has donated 50,000 NIS (approximately $14,000) to Israeli right-wing nationalist organization Im Tirtzu.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The organization, that was declared by Israeli court to have "certain lines of resemblance to fascism", asked to leave the donation private but the Israeli Corporations Authority forced the Organization to publish the donation.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] On February 22, 2022, Coca-Cola announced that the company began to accumulate ingredients for the production of drinks in Russia in order to minimize the damage of the sanctions that Western countries threatened Russia following Moscow's recognition of two breakaway Ukrainian regions.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] After a week of Russian invasion of Ukraine, on March 3, 2022, Coca-Cola announced that the company would not stop working in Russia and that all of Coke's operational, production and logistics facilities in Russia are working.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] As the result, on March 4, 2022, most Ukrainian supermarkets refused to cooperate with Coca-Cola and sell any of Coke's products.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Within days, the campaign to boycott Coca-Cola for its continued operations in Russia had become international.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Celebrities who criticized Coca-Cola over this include American author Stephen King.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] On November 15, 2024, Coca-Cola released its AI-generated Christmas-themed advertisement titled *"The Holiday Magic is Coming."* The video was intended as a tribute to Coca-Cola’s 1995 *"Holidays Are Coming"* commercial, which featured similar imagery but used human actors and real trucks.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The AI-generated nature of the advertisement led to backlash from viewers and artists, with critics arguing that it lacked the authenticity and warmth of its predecessor.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Some also expressed concerns over the implications of replacing human artists with AI-generated content.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In response, a Coca-Cola spokesperson stated: "We are always exploring new ways to connect with consumers and experiment with different approaches.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] This year, we crafted films through a collaboration of human storytellers and the power of generative AI.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] Another AI-generated advertisement was released a year later on November 3, 2025, which received similar criticism.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In November 2000, Coca-Cola agreed to pay $192.5 million to settle a class action racial discrimination lawsuit and promised to change the way it manages, promotes, and treats minority employees in the US.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2003, protesters at Coca-Cola's annual meeting claimed that black people remained underrepresented in top management at the company, were paid less than white employees, and were fired more often.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In February 2021, recordings of an employee training course were leaked on social media.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2001, the Sinaltrainal trade union filed a suit against Coca-Cola in a Miami district court.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The union alleged that two Coca-Cola bottling partners, Bebidas y Alimentos and Panamco, assisted paramilitaries in murdering several union members.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] The court decided charges would be considered against the partners but not Coca-Cola itself.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] On September 4, 2006, Judge Martinez dismissed the remaining claims against the two bottlers.
[src:criticism-of-coca-cola/criticism-of-coca-cola] In 2005, 105 Coca-Cola employees in Turkey were terminated for their union activity and these employees, some of whom were joined by family members, were physically attacked by members of the Cevik Kuvvet during peaceful demonstrations against their terminations.
